metadata.name: Paleterum #136
metadata.description:
Notes: GPU intensive. May not render on some mobile devices. Renders fastest with Chrome.

Controls:
Press “s” to save .png
Press 1-4 to change resolution:
1 - 1000px * 1410px
2 - 2000px * 2820px 
3 - 3000px * 4230px
4 - 4000px * 5640px 

Default resolution is 1000px * 1410px. It is recommended to explore in 2000px * 2820px or above.

Paleterum (latin “plate”, “board”) — a flat surface that is used by artists to hold and mix colors.
This artwork is an attempt to simulate the look of watercolor on paper. Inspired by childhood memories that passed through the watercolor sketches of my mother, who was an artist, the piece reflects my admiration for her work and her influence on my own artistic endeavors. 
Intricate forms contrast with the strict forms of cells. All these are echoes from childhood - watercolor lines of a child not bothered by a special artistic idea but trying at least to a fraction of mastering the fine arts and cubes reminiscent of ones which children use to build towers.
Overall, the piece is a tribute to the joy and creativity of childhood, and to the power of artistic inspiration that can be passed down from one generation to the next.

Made with p5js and a few GLSL shaders.

metadata.name: Scattered Pathways #423
metadata.description:
"Scattered Pathways" studies pathfinding on a grid. I enjoy watching the sketch find and fill the available spaces. I hope you enjoy this one too!

Royalties Splits:
50% Donation to minter

Features:
Two different sizes: 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
@liamegan1/fxhash-helpers
@altesc/stdio

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: rive #574
metadata.description:
Starting with a repeatable system of colors and/or triangles typically seen in geometric abstraction, rive employs generative art to break/split/rive those patterns–and the comfort we find in them–in slight, seemingly unintentional ways.  With each subsequent split, our comfort fades as the artwork is shredded into barely recognizable fragments of a once carefully orchestrated pattern.

Not all rivings are created equal; some are subtle and barely visible while others are acute and violent.  

What holds it together is what breaks it apart.  

created using triangles and p5js

rive
abstractment, 2022

___________________________

Functionality:
Press ‘p’ to save as a png.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality. 0 to 9 (highest quality, ~15k x ~15k, depending on the dimensions).  The window background will change colors when completed rendering.
Press ⬆️ (arrow up) to increase pixel density by 0.5.
Press ⬇️ (arrow down) to decrease pixel density by 0.5.

metadata.name: Canevach #44
metadata.description:
Canevach started as a code golfing experiment, 280 characters of HTML, CSS and JavaScript producing pixelated patterns when copy-pasted in the address bar of a web browser.

The code has been adapted for the sake of entropy control and readability, but I tried to keep it as lean as possible to honour the code golfing spirit that initiated the project.

The artwork is generated by manipulating pixels directly through the Canvas API.

Colours are uniformly selected in RGB space, without any colour theory considerations. The only exception is for black, which is made more prominent by the way the algorithm is initiated.

Features
• Canvas size: 8x8 | 16x16 | 32x32 | 64x64 | 128x128
• Number of colours: 1 to 5

fx(hash) Generative Token by loackme

metadata.name: Anarchy #84
metadata.description:
"Anarchy" aims to pay tribute to the Impressionist masters and explore the interplay between randomness and control. My goal was to capture the bold use of color and the fleeting nature of light and movement that is so characteristic of the Abstract Impressionist style. 

This piece uses a total of 12 color palettes, each one inspired by a different Impressionist painter. Some artists have two palette variations, while others only have one.

I wanted to create something that was unique and that would reflect my own visual emotions while also paying homage to the artists that inspire me. "Anarchy" is part of my exploration of the relationship between randomness and intention, and a celebration of the enduring legacy of the Impressionist masters.

Made by wandurz using p5.js 
January 2023
